{"parentUuid":"15c2b168-c061-4419-aaaa-3e40e57b2ace","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01SaBCspft9W3cYKd67JdsiP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VQDR5ghZafEQtKFkhr1zRb","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/nick/repos/serval/docs/plans/2026-03-29-lb-health-findings-fixes.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":991,"cache_read_input_tokens":70543,"output_tokens":97,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":991,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZXjApRbaQuDhDvnP6Rqm","type":"assistant","uuid":"bdcf9063-0077-42a5-8999-3f170d634aa3","timestamp":"2026-03-29T16:59:31.957Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/nick/repos/serval","sessionId":"646a4f49-bebb-4328-acf0-8f573ea592f5","version":"2.1.86","gitBranch":"main","slug":"graceful-swimming-stream"}
{"parentUuid":"bdcf9063-0077-42a5-8999-3f170d634aa3","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"2267ac92-9597-4089-a154-3f3228d90526","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VQDR5ghZafEQtKFkhr1zRb","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# LB/Health Findings Fixes Implementation Plan\n2\t\n3\t> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n4\t\n5\t**Goal:** Fix 5 audit findings in serval-lb/serval-health/serval-prober: data race on health counters, unvalidated upstream.idx, silent TLS misconfiguration, slow prober shutdown, and stale README.\n6\t\n7\t**Architecture:** Add a mutex to HealthState to protect counter read-modify-write sequences (bitmap reads stay lock-free). Add init-time validation in LbHandler for upstream idx density and TLS context requirements. Replace the single long sleep in scheduler with an interruptible polling loop. Update README to match current API.\n8\t\n9\t**Tech Stack:** Zig 0.16, std.Thread.Mutex, std.atomic\n10\t\n11\t---\n12\t\n13\t### Task 1: Fix data race on health counters (Finding 1 - High)\n14\t\n15\tThe `failure_counts` and `success_counts` arrays are plain `[MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8`. Both the request path (`onLog` -> `recordFailure`/`recordSuccess`) and the prober thread (`probeUnhealthyOnce` -> `recordSuccess`) write these concurrently. The bitmap itself is atomic, but the counter read-modify-write sequences are not protected.\n16\t\n17\t**Files:**\n18\t- Modify: `serval-health/health_state.zig`\n19\t\n20\t**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n21\t\n22\tAdd a concurrent write test to `serval-health/tests.zig` that exercises both `recordFailure` and `recordSuccess` from multiple threads simultaneously. This test exercises the exact race pattern: request-path threads calling `recordFailure` while prober-like threads call `recordSuccess` on the same backend.\n23\t\n24\t```zig\n25\ttest \"concurrent writes are thread-safe\" {\n26\t    // Simulates request path (recordFailure) + prober (recordSuccess) racing.\n27\t    var hs = HealthState.init(MAX_UPSTREAMS, 3, 2);\n28\t\n29\t    const Context = struct {\n30\t        hs: *HealthState,\n31\t    };\n32\t\n33\t    const failure_worker = struct {\n34\t        fn run(ctx: *Context) void {\n35\t            var iteration: u32 = 0;\n36\t            while (iteration < ITERATIONS_PER_THREAD) : (iteration += 1) {\n37\t                const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(iteration % MAX_UPSTREAMS);\n38\t                ctx.hs.recordFailure(idx);\n39\t            }\n40\t        }\n41\t    }.run;\n42\t\n43\t    const success_worker = struct {\n44\t        fn run(ctx: *Context) void {\n45\t            var iteration: u32 = 0;\n46\t            while (iteration < ITERATIONS_PER_THREAD) : (iteration += 1) {\n47\t                const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(iteration % MAX_UPSTREAMS);\n48\t                ctx.hs.recordSuccess(idx);\n49\t            }\n50\t        }\n51\t    }.run;\n52\t\n53\t    var ctx = Context{ .hs = &hs };\n54\t\n55\t    var threads: [CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT]Thread = undefined;\n56\t    var spawned: u32 = 0;\n57\t\n58\t    // Half failure workers, half success workers\n59\t    while (spawned < CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT) : (spawned += 1) {\n60\t        if (spawned % 2 == 0) {\n61\t            threads[spawned] = Thread.spawn(.{}, failure_worker, .{&ctx}) catch unreachable;\n62\t        } else {\n63\t            threads[spawned] = Thread.spawn(.{}, success_worker, .{&ctx}) catch unreachable;\n64\t        }\n65\t    }\n66\t\n67\t    var joined: u32 = 0;\n68\t    while (joined < CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT) : (joined += 1) {\n69\t        threads[joined].join();\n70\t    }\n71\t\n72\t    // Invariant: no crash, no UB, counters are bounded\n73\t    for (0..MAX_UPSTREAMS) |i| {\n74\t        const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(i);\n75\t        // counters must be valid u8 values (no torn reads)\n76\t        _ = hs.isHealthy(idx);\n77\t    }\n78\t}\n79\t```\n80\t\n81\t**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails (or exhibits UB under ThreadSanitizer)**\n82\t\n83\tRun: `zig build test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\n84\tExpected: May pass due to race window timing, but is technically UB. The test documents the concurrent usage pattern.\n85\t\n86\t**Step 3: Add mutex to HealthState and protect counter operations**\n87\t\n88\tIn `serval-health/health_state.zig`, add a mutex field and acquire it around counter read-modify-write in `recordSuccess` and `recordFailure`. The bitmap reads (`isHealthy`, `countHealthy`, `findNthHealthy`, `findFirstHealthy`) remain lock-free since they only touch the atomic bitmap.\n89\t\n90\tAdd field to struct (after `healthy_threshold`):\n91\t\n92\t```zig\n93\t    /// Mutex protecting failure_counts/success_counts read-modify-write.\n94\t    /// Bitmap reads (isHealthy, countHealthy, findNthHealthy) stay lock-free.\n95\t    counter_mutex: std.Thread.Mutex,\n96\t```\n97\t\n98\tInitialize in `init`:\n99\t\n100\t```zig\n101\t        return HealthState{\n102\t            .health_bitmap = std.atomic.Value(u64).init(backendMask(backend_count)),\n103\t            .failure_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8),\n104\t            .success_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8),\n105\t            .backend_count = backend_count,\n106\t            .unhealthy_threshold = unhealthy_threshold,\n107\t            .healthy_threshold = healthy_threshold,\n108\t            .counter_mutex = .{},\n109\t        };\n110\t```\n111\t\n112\tIn `reset`:\n113\t\n114\t```zig\n115\t    pub fn reset(self: *HealthState) void {\n116\t        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n117\t        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n118\t        self.health_bitmap.store(backendMask(self.backend_count), .release);\n119\t        self.failure_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8);\n120\t        self.success_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8);\n121\t    }\n122\t```\n123\t\n124\tWrap `recordSuccess` body:\n125\t\n126\t```zig\n127\t    pub inline fn recordSuccess(self: *HealthState, idx: UpstreamIndex) void {\n128\t        assert(idx < self.backend_count);\n129\t\n130\t        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n131\t        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n132\t\n133\t        self.failure_counts[idx] = 0;\n134\t        if (self.isHealthy(idx)) return;\n135\t\n136\t        const new_count = self.success_counts[idx] +| 1;\n137\t        self.success_counts[idx] = new_count;\n138\t\n139\t        if (new_count >= self.healthy_threshold) {\n140\t            self.markHealthy(idx);\n141\t            self.success_counts[idx] = 0;\n142\t        }\n143\t    }\n144\t```\n145\t\n146\tWrap `recordFailure` body identically:\n147\t\n148\t```zig\n149\t    pub inline fn recordFailure(self: *HealthState, idx: UpstreamIndex) void {\n150\t        assert(idx < self.backend_count);\n151\t\n152\t        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n153\t        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n154\t\n155\t        self.success_counts[idx] = 0;\n156\t        if (!self.isHealthy(idx)) return;\n157\t\n158\t        const new_count = self.failure_counts[idx] +| 1;\n159\t        self.failure_counts[idx] = new_count;\n160\t\n161\t        if (new_count >= self.unhealthy_threshold) {\n162\t            self.markUnhealthy(idx);\n163\t            self.failure_counts[idx] = 0;\n164\t        }\n165\t    }\n166\t```\n167\t\n168\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n169\t\n170\tRun: `zig build test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\n171\tExpected: All tests PASS (existing + new concurrent write test).\n172\t\n173\t**Step 5: Commit**\n174\t\n175\t```bash\n176\tgit add serval-health/health_state.zig serval-health/tests.zig\n177\tgit commit -m \"fix(health): add mutex to protect counter read-modify-write from data race\n178\t\n179\tPassive health updates (request path) and active probing (background thread)\n180\tboth write failure_counts/success_counts concurrently. Bitmap reads remain\n181\tlock-free.\"\n182\t```\n183\t\n184\t---\n185\t\n186\t### Task 2: Validate upstream.idx at LB init (Finding 2 - High)\n187\t\n188\t`onLog` uses `entry.upstream.idx` as an array index into health state. No init-time check ensures each upstream's idx forms a dense 0..N-1 range. In release builds (asserts stripped), an out-of-range or non-dense idx silently corrupts health state.\n189\t\n190\t**Files:**\n191\t- Modify: `serval-lb/handler.zig`\n192\t\n193\t**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n194\t\n195\tAdd tests to `serval-lb/handler.zig` that verify init rejects non-dense upstream indices.\n196\t\n197\t```zig\n198\ttest \"LbHandler init rejects non-dense upstream idx\" {\n199\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n200\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n201\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8002, .idx = 5 }, // gap: should be 1\n202\t    };\n203\t\n204\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n205\t    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n206\t    try std.testing.expectError(error.InvalidUpstreamIndex, result);\n207\t}\n208\t\n209\ttest \"LbHandler init rejects duplicate upstream idx\" {\n210\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n211\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n212\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8002, .idx = 0 }, // duplicate\n213\t    };\n214\t\n215\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n216\t    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n217\t    try std.testing.expectError(error.InvalidUpstreamIndex, result);\n218\t}\n219\t```\n220\t\n221\t**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n222\t\n223\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n224\tExpected: Compile error (error.InvalidUpstreamIndex doesn't exist yet) or assertion panic.\n225\t\n226\t**Step 3: Add idx validation to LbHandler.init**\n227\t\n228\tAdd a validation block in `handler.zig` `init`, after the existing asserts and before setting `self.*`. This validates that upstream indices form a dense 0..N-1 permutation.\n229\t\n230\tAdd error type above the struct:\n231\t\n232\t```zig\n233\tpub const LbError = error{\n234\t    InvalidUpstreamIndex,\n235\t    TlsContextRequired,\n236\t};\n237\t```\n238\t\n239\tChange `init` return type from `!void` to `LbError!void`.\n240\t\n241\tAdd validation in `init` after the existing asserts, before `self.* = .{`:\n242\t\n243\t```zig\n244\t        // Validate upstream indices are a dense 0..N-1 permutation.\n245\t        // Prevents health state corruption from misconfigured idx values.\n246\t        var idx_seen: u64 = 0;\n247\t        for (upstreams) |upstream| {\n248\t            if (upstream.idx >= upstreams.len) return LbError.InvalidUpstreamIndex;\n249\t            const mask: u64 = @as(u64, 1) << @as(u6, @intCast(upstream.idx));\n250\t            if (idx_seen & mask != 0) return LbError.InvalidUpstreamIndex; // duplicate\n251\t            idx_seen |= mask;\n252\t        }\n253\t```\n254\t\n255\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n256\t\n257\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n258\tExpected: All tests PASS.\n259\t\n260\t**Step 5: Commit**\n261\t\n262\t```bash\n263\tgit add serval-lb/handler.zig\n264\tgit commit -m \"fix(lb): validate upstream.idx is dense 0..N-1 at init\n265\t\n266\tPrevents health state corruption from misconfigured idx values.\n267\tReturns error.InvalidUpstreamIndex instead of relying on debug asserts.\"\n268\t```\n269\t\n270\t---\n271\t\n272\t### Task 3: Validate TLS context at init when upstreams require TLS (Finding 3 - Medium)\n273\t\n274\tIf any upstream has `tls=true` but `client_ctx` is null, probes silently fail (client returns `TlsHandshakeFailed`, adapter catches as `false`). The backend stays permanently unhealthy with no indication of misconfiguration.\n275\t\n276\t**Files:**\n277\t- Modify: `serval-lb/handler.zig`\n278\t\n279\t**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n280\t\n281\t```zig\n282\ttest \"LbHandler init rejects null client_ctx when upstream has tls=true\" {\n283\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n284\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0, .tls = true },\n285\t    };\n286\t\n287\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n288\t    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = true }, null, null);\n289\t    // Should fail because tls upstream requires client_ctx\n290\t    // (dns_resolver=null also invalid with probing, but TLS check should come first or alongside)\n291\t    try std.testing.expectError(error.TlsContextRequired, result);\n292\t}\n293\t\n294\ttest \"LbHandler init accepts null client_ctx when no upstream has tls\" {\n295\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n296\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0, .tls = false },\n297\t    };\n298\t\n299\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n300\t    // probing disabled so dns_resolver=null is fine\n301\t    try handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n302\t    defer handler.deinit();\n303\t}\n304\t```\n305\t\n306\t**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n307\t\n308\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n309\tExpected: FAIL (error.TlsContextRequired doesn't exist yet).\n310\t\n311\t**Step 3: Add TLS context validation**\n312\t\n313\tIn `handler.zig` `init`, add after the idx validation:\n314\t\n315\t```zig\n316\t        // Validate TLS context when any upstream requires TLS.\n317\t        // Without client_ctx, TLS probes silently fail and backends stay permanently unhealthy.\n318\t        if (client_ctx == null) {\n319\t            for (upstreams) |upstream| {\n320\t                if (upstream.tls) return LbError.TlsContextRequired;\n321\t            }\n322\t        }\n323\t```\n324\t\n325\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n326\t\n327\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n328\tExpected: All tests PASS.\n329\t\n330\t**Step 5: Commit**\n331\t\n332\t```bash\n333\tgit add serval-lb/handler.zig\n334\tgit commit -m \"fix(lb): reject null client_ctx when upstreams require TLS\n335\t\n336\tWithout TLS context, probes silently fail and backends stay permanently\n337\tunhealthy. Now returns error.TlsContextRequired at init.\"\n338\t```\n339\t\n340\t---\n341\t\n342\t### Task 4: Reduce prober shutdown latency (Finding 4 - Medium)\n343\t\n344\t`runLoopWithIo` sleeps for the full probe interval (default 5s) then checks `probe_running`. `deinit()` sets the flag then blocks on `join()`. Worst-case shutdown blocks for the full interval.\n345\t\n346\t**Files:**\n347\t- Modify: `serval-prober/scheduler.zig`\n348\t\n349\t**Step 1: Write the test**\n350\t\n351\tThe existing `probeUnhealthyOnce` test covers probe logic. Add a test verifying the shutdown flag is checked between sleep increments. Since we can't easily test timing, we test that the loop exits promptly when `probe_running` is false from the start.\n352\t\n353\t```zig\n354\ttest \"runLoopWithIo exits immediately when probe_running is false\" {\n355\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n356\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n357\t    };\n358\t\n359\t    var health = HealthState.init(1, 1, 1);\n360\t    var running = std.atomic.Value(bool).init(false); // already stopped\n361\t\n362\t    var adapter_marker: u8 = 0;\n363\t    const NoopAdapter = struct {\n364\t        fn probe(context: *anyopaque, upstream: Upstream, io_arg: Io) bool {\n365\t            _ = context;\n366\t            _ = upstream;\n367\t            _ = io_arg;\n368\t            return false;\n369\t        }\n370\t    };\n371\t\n372\t    const ctx = SchedulerContext{\n373\t        .upstreams = &upstreams,\n374\t        .health = &health,\n375\t        .probe_running = &running,\n376\t        .probe_interval_ms = 60_000, // 60 seconds - would hang if not interruptible\n377\t        .adapter = .{\n378\t            .context = &adapter_marker,\n379\t            .probeFn = NoopAdapter.probe,\n380\t        },\n381\t    };\n382\t\n383\t    // This should return near-instantly, not block for 60 seconds\n384\t    runLoopWithIo(ctx, undefined);\n385\t}\n386\t```\n387\t\n388\t**Step 2: Run test**\n389\t\n390\tRun: `zig build