{"parentUuid":"b05188dc-f4ef-40ac-adea-e3d15521c3a3","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"1509fa14-f151-4a41-b23d-dc0d46f69dfc","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SdMXJnXDWmra1YqdQoY1ep","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# LB/Health Findings Fixes Implementation Plan\n2\t\n3\t> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n4\t\n5\t**Goal:** Fix 5 audit findings in serval-lb/serval-health/serval-prober: data race on health counters, unvalidated upstream.idx, silent TLS misconfiguration, slow prober shutdown, and stale README.\n6\t\n7\t**Architecture:** Add a mutex to HealthState to protect counter read-modify-write sequences (bitmap reads stay lock-free). Add init-time validation in LbHandler for upstream idx density and TLS context requirements. Replace the single long sleep in scheduler with an interruptible polling loop. Update README to match current API.\n8\t\n9\t**Tech Stack:** Zig 0.16, std.Thread.Mutex, std.atomic\n10\t\n11\t---\n12\t\n13\t### Task 1: Fix data race on health counters (Finding 1 - High)\n14\t\n15\tThe `failure_counts` and `success_counts` arrays are plain `[MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8`. Both the request path (`onLog` -> `recordFailure`/`recordSuccess`) and the prober thread (`probeUnhealthyOnce` -> `recordSuccess`) write these concurrently. The bitmap itself is atomic, but the counter read-modify-write sequences are not protected.\n16\t\n17\t**Files:**\n18\t- Modify: `serval-health/health_state.zig`\n19\t\n20\t**Step 1: Write concurrent stress test**\n21\t\n22\tAdd a concurrent write stress test to `serval-health/tests.zig` that exercises both `recordFailure` and `recordSuccess` from multiple threads simultaneously. This test exercises the exact race pattern: request-path threads calling `recordFailure` while prober-like threads call `recordSuccess` on the same backend. Note: data races are timing-dependent and may not deterministically fail before the fix; this test documents the concurrent contract and will catch regressions/UB under sanitizers.\n23\t\n24\t```zig\n25\ttest \"concurrent writes are thread-safe\" {\n26\t    // Simulates request path (recordFailure) + prober (recordSuccess) racing.\n27\t    var hs = HealthState.init(MAX_UPSTREAMS, 3, 2);\n28\t\n29\t    const Context = struct {\n30\t        hs: *HealthState,\n31\t    };\n32\t\n33\t    const failure_worker = struct {\n34\t        fn run(ctx: *Context) void {\n35\t            var iteration: u32 = 0;\n36\t            while (iteration < ITERATIONS_PER_THREAD) : (iteration += 1) {\n37\t                const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(iteration % MAX_UPSTREAMS);\n38\t                ctx.hs.recordFailure(idx);\n39\t            }\n40\t        }\n41\t    }.run;\n42\t\n43\t    const success_worker = struct {\n44\t        fn run(ctx: *Context) void {\n45\t            var iteration: u32 = 0;\n46\t            while (iteration < ITERATIONS_PER_THREAD) : (iteration += 1) {\n47\t                const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(iteration % MAX_UPSTREAMS);\n48\t                ctx.hs.recordSuccess(idx);\n49\t            }\n50\t        }\n51\t    }.run;\n52\t\n53\t    var ctx = Context{ .hs = &hs };\n54\t\n55\t    var threads: [CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT]Thread = undefined;\n56\t    var spawned: u32 = 0;\n57\t\n58\t    // Half failure workers, half success workers\n59\t    while (spawned < CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT) : (spawned += 1) {\n60\t        if (spawned % 2 == 0) {\n61\t            threads[spawned] = Thread.spawn(.{}, failure_worker, .{&ctx}) catch unreachable;\n62\t        } else {\n63\t            threads[spawned] = Thread.spawn(.{}, success_worker, .{&ctx}) catch unreachable;\n64\t        }\n65\t    }\n66\t\n67\t    var joined: u32 = 0;\n68\t    while (joined < CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT) : (joined += 1) {\n69\t        threads[joined].join();\n70\t    }\n71\t\n72\t    // Invariant: no crash, no UB, counters are bounded\n73\t    for (0..MAX_UPSTREAMS) |i| {\n74\t        const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(i);\n75\t        // counters must be valid u8 values (no torn reads)\n76\t        _ = hs.isHealthy(idx);\n77\t    }\n78\t}\n79\t```\n80\t\n81\t**Step 2: Run stress test to establish baseline**\n82\t\n83\tRun: `zig build test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\n84\tExpected: Likely passes (race window is timing-dependent), but exercises the concurrent pattern that constitutes UB on non-atomic counters. After the mutex fix, this test guarantees defined behavior under concurrent access.\n85\t\n86\t**Step 3: Add mutex to HealthState and protect counter operations**\n87\t\n88\tIn `serval-health/health_state.zig`, add a mutex field and acquire it around counter read-modify-write in `recordSuccess` and `recordFailure`. The bitmap reads (`isHealthy`, `countHealthy`, `findNthHealthy`, `findFirstHealthy`) remain lock-free since they only touch the atomic bitmap.\n89\t\n90\tAdd field to struct (after `healthy_threshold`):\n91\t\n92\t```zig\n93\t    /// Mutex protecting failure_counts/success_counts read-modify-write.\n94\t    /// Bitmap reads (isHealthy, countHealthy, findNthHealthy) stay lock-free.\n95\t    counter_mutex: std.Thread.Mutex,\n96\t```\n97\t\n98\tInitialize in `init`:\n99\t\n100\t```zig\n101\t        return HealthState{\n102\t            .health_bitmap = std.atomic.Value(u64).init(backendMask(backend_count)),\n103\t            .failure_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8),\n104\t            .success_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8),\n105\t            .backend_count = backend_count,\n106\t            .unhealthy_threshold = unhealthy_threshold,\n107\t            .healthy_threshold = healthy_threshold,\n108\t            .counter_mutex = .{},\n109\t        };\n110\t```\n111\t\n112\tIn `reset`:\n113\t\n114\t```zig\n115\t    pub fn reset(self: *HealthState) void {\n116\t        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n117\t        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n118\t        self.health_bitmap.store(backendMask(self.backend_count), .release);\n119\t        self.failure_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8);\n120\t        self.success_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8);\n121\t    }\n122\t```\n123\t\n124\tWrap `recordSuccess` body:\n125\t\n126\t```zig\n127\t    pub inline fn recordSuccess(self: *HealthState, idx: UpstreamIndex) void {\n128\t        assert(idx < self.backend_count);\n129\t\n130\t        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n131\t        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n132\t\n133\t        self.failure_counts[idx] = 0;\n134\t        if (self.isHealthy(idx)) return;\n135\t\n136\t        const new_count = self.success_counts[idx] +| 1;\n137\t        self.success_counts[idx] = new_count;\n138\t\n139\t        if (new_count >= self.healthy_threshold) {\n140\t            self.markHealthy(idx);\n141\t            self.success_counts[idx] = 0;\n142\t        }\n143\t    }\n144\t```\n145\t\n146\tWrap `recordFailure` body identically:\n147\t\n148\t```zig\n149\t    pub inline fn recordFailure(self: *HealthState, idx: UpstreamIndex) void {\n150\t        assert(idx < self.backend_count);\n151\t\n152\t        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n153\t        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n154\t\n155\t        self.success_counts[idx] = 0;\n156\t        if (!self.isHealthy(idx)) return;\n157\t\n158\t        const new_count = self.failure_counts[idx] +| 1;\n159\t        self.failure_counts[idx] = new_count;\n160\t\n161\t        if (new_count >= self.unhealthy_threshold) {\n162\t            self.markUnhealthy(idx);\n163\t            self.failure_counts[idx] = 0;\n164\t        }\n165\t    }\n166\t```\n167\t\n168\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n169\t\n170\tRun: `zig build test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\n171\tExpected: All tests PASS (existing + new concurrent write test).\n172\t\n173\t**Step 5: Commit**\n174\t\n175\t```bash\n176\tgit add serval-health/health_state.zig serval-health/tests.zig\n177\tgit commit -m \"fix(health): add mutex to protect counter read-modify-write from data race\n178\t\n179\tPassive health updates (request path) and active probing (background thread)\n180\tboth write failure_counts/success_counts concurrently. Bitmap reads remain\n181\tlock-free.\"\n182\t```\n183\t\n184\t---\n185\t\n186\t### Task 2: Validate upstream.idx at LB init (Finding 2 - High)\n187\t\n188\t`onLog` uses `entry.upstream.idx` as an array index into health state. No init-time check ensures each upstream's idx forms a dense 0..N-1 range. In release builds (asserts stripped), an out-of-range or non-dense idx silently corrupts health state.\n189\t\n190\t**Files:**\n191\t- Modify: `serval-lb/handler.zig`\n192\t\n193\t**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n194\t\n195\tAdd tests to `serval-lb/handler.zig` that verify init rejects non-dense upstream indices.\n196\t\n197\t```zig\n198\ttest \"LbHandler init rejects non-dense upstream idx\" {\n199\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n200\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n201\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8002, .idx = 5 }, // gap: should be 1\n202\t    };\n203\t\n204\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n205\t    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n206\t    try std.testing.expectError(error.InvalidUpstreamIndex, result);\n207\t}\n208\t\n209\ttest \"LbHandler init rejects duplicate upstream idx\" {\n210\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n211\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n212\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8002, .idx = 0 }, // duplicate\n213\t    };\n214\t\n215\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n216\t    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n217\t    try std.testing.expectError(error.InvalidUpstreamIndex, result);\n218\t}\n219\t```\n220\t\n221\t**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n222\t\n223\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n224\tExpected: Compile error (error.InvalidUpstreamIndex doesn't exist yet) or assertion panic.\n225\t\n226\t**Step 3: Add idx validation to LbHandler.init**\n227\t\n228\tAdd a validation block in `handler.zig` `init`, after the existing asserts and before setting `self.*`. This validates that upstream indices form a dense 0..N-1 permutation.\n229\t\n230\tKeep `init` return type as `!void` (inferred error set). This is required because `init` also calls `std.Thread.spawn` which returns spawn-related errors not in any named LbError set. The new validation errors (`error.InvalidUpstreamIndex`, `error.TlsContextRequired`) are returned as part of the inferred set alongside existing spawn errors.\n231\t\n232\tAdd validation in `init` after the existing asserts, before `self.* = .{`:\n233\t\n234\t```zig\n235\t        // Validate upstream indices are a dense 0..N-1 permutation.\n236\t        // Prevents health state corruption from misconfigured idx values.\n237\t        var idx_seen: u64 = 0;\n238\t        for (upstreams) |upstream| {\n239\t            if (upstream.idx >= upstreams.len) return error.InvalidUpstreamIndex;\n240\t            const mask: u64 = @as(u64, 1) << @as(u6, @intCast(upstream.idx));\n241\t            if (idx_seen & mask != 0) return error.InvalidUpstreamIndex; // duplicate\n242\t            idx_seen |= mask;\n243\t        }\n244\t```\n245\t\n246\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n247\t\n248\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n249\tExpected: All tests PASS.\n250\t\n251\t**Step 5: Commit**\n252\t\n253\t```bash\n254\tgit add serval-lb/handler.zig\n255\tgit commit -m \"fix(lb): validate upstream.idx is dense 0..N-1 at init\n256\t\n257\tPrevents health state corruption from misconfigured idx values.\n258\tReturns error.InvalidUpstreamIndex instead of relying on debug asserts.\"\n259\t```\n260\t\n261\t---\n262\t\n263\t### Task 3: Validate TLS context at init when upstreams require TLS (Finding 3 - Medium)\n264\t\n265\tIf any upstream has `tls=true` but `client_ctx` is null, probes silently fail (client returns `TlsHandshakeFailed`, adapter catches as `false`). The backend stays permanently unhealthy with no indication of misconfiguration.\n266\t\n267\t**Files:**\n268\t- Modify: `serval-lb/handler.zig`\n269\t\n270\t**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n271\t\n272\tNote: The existing assert at `handler.zig:85` checks `!enable_probing or dns_resolver != null` and would panic before the TLS check if `dns_resolver` is null with probing enabled. The test must provide a valid `dns_resolver` to reach the TLS validation path.\n273\t\n274\t```zig\n275\ttest \"LbHandler init rejects null client_ctx when upstream has tls=true\" {\n276\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n277\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0, .tls = true },\n278\t    };\n279\t\n280\t    // Provide dns_resolver so the existing probing assert at handler.zig:85 passes.\n281\t    // The TLS validation fires after that assert.\n282\t    var dns_resolver: DnsResolver = undefined;\n283\t    DnsResolver.init(&dns_resolver, .{});\n284\t\n285\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n286\t    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = true }, null, &dns_resolver);\n287\t    try std.testing.expectError(error.TlsContextRequired, result);\n288\t}\n289\t\n290\ttest \"LbHandler init accepts null client_ctx when no upstream has tls\" {\n291\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n292\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0, .tls = false },\n293\t    };\n294\t\n295\t    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n296\t    // probing disabled so dns_resolver=null is fine, and no TLS upstreams so client_ctx=null is fine\n297\t    try handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n298\t    defer handler.deinit();\n299\t}\n300\t```\n301\t\n302\t**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n303\t\n304\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n305\tExpected: FAIL (error.TlsContextRequired doesn't exist yet).\n306\t\n307\t**Step 3: Add TLS context validation**\n308\t\n309\tIn `handler.zig` `init`, add after the idx validation:\n310\t\n311\t```zig\n312\t        // Validate TLS context when probing is enabled and any upstream requires TLS.\n313\t        // Without client_ctx, TLS probes silently fail and backends stay permanently unhealthy.\n314\t        // Only relevant when probing is active — without probing, no TLS handshakes are attempted\n315\t        // by the LbHandler (request-path TLS uses its own client_ctx from the Client).\n316\t        if (lb_config.enable_probing and client_ctx == null) {\n317\t            for (upstreams) |upstream| {\n318\t                if (upstream.tls) return error.TlsContextRequired;\n319\t            }\n320\t        }\n321\t```\n322\t\n323\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n324\t\n325\tRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\n326\tExpected: All tests PASS.\n327\t\n328\t**Step 5: Commit**\n329\t\n330\t```bash\n331\tgit add serval-lb/handler.zig\n332\tgit commit -m \"fix(lb): reject null client_ctx when upstreams require TLS\n333\t\n334\tWithout TLS context, probes silently fail and backends stay permanently\n335\tunhealthy. Now returns error.TlsContextRequired at init.\"\n336\t```\n337\t\n338\t---\n339\t\n340\t### Task 4: Reduce prober shutdown latency (Finding 4 - Medium)\n341\t\n342\t`runLoopWithIo` sleeps for the full probe interval (default 5s) then checks `probe_running`. `deinit()` sets the flag then blocks on `join()`. Worst-case shutdown blocks for the full interval.\n343\t\n344\t**Files:**\n345\t- Modify: `serval-prober/scheduler.zig`\n346\t\n347\t**Step 1: Write the test**\n348\t\n349\tThe existing `probeUnhealthyOnce` test covers probe logic. Add a test verifying the shutdown flag is checked between sleep increments. Since we can't easily test timing, we test that the loop exits promptly when `probe_running` is false from the start.\n350\t\n351\t```zig\n352\ttest \"runLoopWithIo exits immediately when probe_running is false\" {\n353\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n354\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n355\t    };\n356\t\n357\t    var health = HealthState.init(1, 1, 1);\n358\t    var running = std.atomic.Value(bool).init(false); // already stopped\n359\t\n360\t    var adapter_marker: u8 = 0;\n361\t    const NoopAdapter = struct {\n362\t        fn probe(context: *anyopaque, upstream: Upstream, io_arg: Io) bool {\n363\t            _ = context;\n364\t            _ = upstream;\n365\t            _ = io_arg;\n366\t            return false;\n367\t        }\n368\t    };\n369\t\n370\t    const ctx = SchedulerContext{\n371\t        .upstreams = &upstreams,\n372\t        .health = &health,\n373\t        .probe_running = &running,\n374\t        .probe_interval_ms = 60_000, // 60 seconds - would hang if not interruptible\n375\t        .adapter = .{\n376\t            .context = &adapter_marker,\n377\t            .probeFn = NoopAdapter.probe,\n378\t        },\n379\t    };\n380\t\n381\t    // This should return near-instantly, not block for 60 seconds\n382\t    runLoopWithIo(ctx, undefined);\n383\t}\n384\t```\n385\t\n386\t**Step 2: Run test**\n387\t\n388\tRun: `zig build test 2>&1 | grep -A2 \"runLoopWithIo exits\"`\n389\tExpected: PASS (current code already checks flag before sleep, so this passes). The real improvement is the sleep granularity change.\n390\t\n391\t**Step 3: Replace single long sleep with interruptible polling loop**\n392\t\n393\tIn `scheduler.zig`, replace the single `Io.sleep` call with a loop of shorter sleeps (100ms increments) that checks `probe_running` between each:\n394\t\n395\tReplace the `runLoopWithIo` function:\n396\t\n397\t```zig\n398\t/// Maximum sleep granularity for interruptible shutdown (100ms).\n399\tconst SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS: u32 = 100;\n400\t\n401\tpub fn runLoopWithIo(ctx: SchedulerContext, io: Io) void {\n402\t    assert(ctx.probe_interval_ms > 0);\n403\t\n404\t    while (ctx.probe_running.load(.acquire)) {\n405\t        probeUnhealthyOnce(ctx, io);\n406\t        // Sleep in small increments so shutdown is responsive.\n407\t        interruptibleSleep(ctx.probe_running, ctx.probe_interval_ms, io);\n408\t    }\n409\t}\n410\t\n411\t/// Sleep for `total_ms` in increments of SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS, checking the\n412\t/// stop flag between each increment. Returns early if flag becomes false.\n413\tfn interruptibleSleep(\n414\t    probe_running: *std.atomic.Value(bool),\n415\t    total_ms: u32,\n416\t    io: Io,\n417\t) void {\n418\t    var remaining_ms: u32 = total_ms;\n419\t    while (remaining_ms > 0 and probe_running.load(.acquire)) {\n420\t        const sleep_ms = @min(remaining_ms, SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS);\n421\t        const duration = std.Io.Duration.fromMilliseconds(@intCast(sleep_ms));\n422\t        std.Io.sleep(std.Options.debug_io, duration, .awake) catch |err| {\n423\t            log.debug(\"interruptible sleep failed: {s}\", .{@errorName(err)});\n424\t        };\n425\t        remaining_ms -= sleep_ms;\n426\t    }\n427\t}\n428\t```\n429\t\n430\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n431\t\n432\tRun: `zig build test 2>&1 | tail -20`\n433\tExpected: All PASS. Note: there is no dedicated `test-prober` build step; `zig build test` runs all library tests including the prober scheduler tests.\n434\t\n435\t**Step 5: Commit**\n436\t\n437\t```bash\n438\tgit add serval-prober/scheduler.zig\n439\tgit commit -m \"fix(prober): reduce shutdown latency with interruptible sleep\n440\t\n441\tReplaces single long sleep with 100ms polling loop that checks\n442\tprobe_running between increments. Worst-case shutdown delay is\n443\tnow ~100ms instead of the full probe interval.\"\n444\t```\n445\t\n446\t---\n447\t\n448\t### Task 5: Update serval-lb README (Finding 5 - Low)\n449\t\n450\tThe usage example calls `handler.init` with old 2-arg signature; current API requires `client_ctx` and `dns_resolver`. The struct snippet shows fields (`health`, `next_idx`) that now live in `RoundRobinStrategy`.\n451\t\n452\t**Files:**\n453\t- Modify: `serval-lb/README.md`\n454\t\n455\t**Step 1: Update usage example**\n456\t\n457\tChange the init call at line 44 to match current signature:\n458\t\n459\t```zig\n460\tvar handler: serval_lb.LbHandler = undefined;\n461\ttry handler.init(&upstreams, .{\n462\t    .unhealthy_threshold = 3,\n463\t    .healthy_threshold = 2,\n464\t    .probe_interval_ms = 5000,\n465\t    .probe_timeout_ms = 2000,\n466\t    .health_path = \"/health\",\n467\t}, client_ctx, &dns_resolver);\n468\tdefer handler.deinit();\n469\t```\n470\t\n471\t**Step 2: Update struct snippet**\n472\t\n473\tReplace the LbHandler struct snippet (line 57) to match actual fields:\n474\t\n475\t```zig\n476\tpub const LbHandler = struct {\n477\t    upstreams: []const Upstream,\n478\t    strategy: RoundRobinStrategy,\n479\t    probe_running: std.atomic.Value(bool),\n480\t    probe_thread: ?std.Thread,\n481\t    lb_config: LbConfig,\n482\t\n483\t    pub fn init(self: *Self, upstreams: []const Upstream, lb_config: LbConfig, client_ctx: ?*ssl.SSL_CTX, dns_resolver: ?*DnsResolver) !void\n484\t    pub fn deinit(self: *Self) void\n485\t    pub fn selectUpstream(self: *Self, ctx: *Context, request: *const Request) Upstream\n486\t    pub fn onLog(self: *Self, ctx: *Context, entry: LogEntry) void\n487\t    pub fn countHealthy(self: *const Self) u32\n488\t    pub fn isHealthy(self: *const Self, idx: UpstreamIndex) bool\n489\t};\n490\t```\n491\t\n492\t**Step 3: Commit**\n493\t\n494\t```bash\n495\tgit add serval-lb/README.md\n496\tgit commit -m \"docs(lb): update README to match current init signature and struct fields\"\n497\t```\n498\t\n499\t---\n500\t\n501\t### Task 6: Run full test suite\n502\t\n503\t**Step 1: Run all unit tests**\n504\t\n505\tRun: `zig build test 2>&1 | tail -20`\n506\tExpected: All PASS.\n507\t\n508\t**Step 2: Run LB and health tests specifically**\n509\t\n510\tRun: `zig build test-lb test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\n511\tExpected: All PASS.\n512\t"}]},"uuid":"1746ff14-96e8-43da-b11a-071ae592bb0d","timestamp":"2026-03-29T17:06:08.001Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/nick/repos/serval/docs/plans/2026-03-29-lb-health-findings-fixes.md","content":"# LB/Health Findings Fixes Implementation Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n\n**Goal:** Fix 5 audit findings in serval-lb/serval-health/serval-prober: data race on health counters, unvalidated upstream.idx, silent TLS misconfiguration, slow prober shutdown, and stale README.\n\n**Architecture:** Add a mutex to HealthState to protect counter read-modify-write sequences (bitmap reads stay lock-free). Add init-time validation in LbHandler for upstream idx density and TLS context requirements. Replace the single long sleep in scheduler with an interruptible polling loop. Update README to match current API.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Zig 0.16, std.Thread.Mutex, std.atomic\n\n---\n\n### Task 1: Fix data race on health counters (Finding 1 - High)\n\nThe `failure_counts` and `success_counts` arrays are plain `[MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8`. Both the request path (`onLog` -> `recordFailure`/`recordSuccess`) and the prober thread (`probeUnhealthyOnce` -> `recordSuccess`) write these concurrently. The bitmap itself is atomic, but the counter read-modify-write sequences are not protected.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `serval-health/health_state.zig`\n\n**Step 1: Write concurrent stress test**\n\nAdd a concurrent write stress test to `serval-health/tests.zig` that exercises both `recordFailure` and `recordSuccess` from multiple threads simultaneously. This test exercises the exact race pattern: request-path threads calling `recordFailure` while prober-like threads call `recordSuccess` on the same backend. Note: data races are timing-dependent and may not deterministically fail before the fix; this test documents the concurrent contract and will catch regressions/UB under sanitizers.\n\n```zig\ntest \"concurrent writes are thread-safe\" {\n    // Simulates request path (recordFailure) + prober (recordSuccess) racing.\n    var hs = HealthState.init(MAX_UPSTREAMS, 3, 2);\n\n    const Context = struct {\n        hs: *HealthState,\n    };\n\n    const failure_worker = struct {\n        fn run(ctx: *Context) void {\n            var iteration: u32 = 0;\n            while (iteration < ITERATIONS_PER_THREAD) : (iteration += 1) {\n                const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(iteration % MAX_UPSTREAMS);\n                ctx.hs.recordFailure(idx);\n            }\n        }\n    }.run;\n\n    const success_worker = struct {\n        fn run(ctx: *Context) void {\n            var iteration: u32 = 0;\n            while (iteration < ITERATIONS_PER_THREAD) : (iteration += 1) {\n                const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(iteration % MAX_UPSTREAMS);\n                ctx.hs.recordSuccess(idx);\n            }\n        }\n    }.run;\n\n    var ctx = Context{ .hs = &hs };\n\n    var threads: [CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT]Thread = undefined;\n    var spawned: u32 = 0;\n\n    // Half failure workers, half success workers\n    while (spawned < CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT) : (spawned += 1) {\n        if (spawned % 2 == 0) {\n            threads[spawned] = Thread.spawn(.{}, failure_worker, .{&ctx}) catch unreachable;\n        } else {\n            threads[spawned] = Thread.spawn(.{}, success_worker, .{&ctx}) catch unreachable;\n        }\n    }\n\n    var joined: u32 = 0;\n    while (joined < CONCURRENT_THREAD_COUNT) : (joined += 1) {\n        threads[joined].join();\n    }\n\n    // Invariant: no crash, no UB, counters are bounded\n    for (0..MAX_UPSTREAMS) |i| {\n        const idx: UpstreamIndex = @intCast(i);\n        // counters must be valid u8 values (no torn reads)\n        _ = hs.isHealthy(idx);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run stress test to establish baseline**\n\nRun: `zig build test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: Likely passes (race window is timing-dependent), but exercises the concurrent pattern that constitutes UB on non-atomic counters. After the mutex fix, this test guarantees defined behavior under concurrent access.\n\n**Step 3: Add mutex to HealthState and protect counter operations**\n\nIn `serval-health/health_state.zig`, add a mutex field and acquire it around counter read-modify-write in `recordSuccess` and `recordFailure`. The bitmap reads (`isHealthy`, `countHealthy`, `findNthHealthy`, `findFirstHealthy`) remain lock-free since they only touch the atomic bitmap.\n\nAdd field to struct (after `healthy_threshold`):\n\n```zig\n    /// Mutex protecting failure_counts/success_counts read-modify-write.\n    /// Bitmap reads (isHealthy, countHealthy, findNthHealthy) stay lock-free.\n    counter_mutex: std.Thread.Mutex,\n```\n\nInitialize in `init`:\n\n```zig\n        return HealthState{\n            .health_bitmap = std.atomic.Value(u64).init(backendMask(backend_count)),\n            .failure_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8),\n            .success_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8),\n            .backend_count = backend_count,\n            .unhealthy_threshold = unhealthy_threshold,\n            .healthy_threshold = healthy_threshold,\n            .counter_mutex = .{},\n        };\n```\n\nIn `reset`:\n\n```zig\n    pub fn reset(self: *HealthState) void {\n        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n        self.health_bitmap.store(backendMask(self.backend_count), .release);\n        self.failure_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8);\n        self.success_counts = std.mem.zeroes([MAX_UPSTREAMS]u8);\n    }\n```\n\nWrap `recordSuccess` body:\n\n```zig\n    pub inline fn recordSuccess(self: *HealthState, idx: UpstreamIndex) void {\n        assert(idx < self.backend_count);\n\n        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n\n        self.failure_counts[idx] = 0;\n        if (self.isHealthy(idx)) return;\n\n        const new_count = self.success_counts[idx] +| 1;\n        self.success_counts[idx] = new_count;\n\n        if (new_count >= self.healthy_threshold) {\n            self.markHealthy(idx);\n            self.success_counts[idx] = 0;\n        }\n    }\n```\n\nWrap `recordFailure` body identically:\n\n```zig\n    pub inline fn recordFailure(self: *HealthState, idx: UpstreamIndex) void {\n        assert(idx < self.backend_count);\n\n        self.counter_mutex.lock();\n        defer self.counter_mutex.unlock();\n\n        self.success_counts[idx] = 0;\n        if (!self.isHealthy(idx)) return;\n\n        const new_count = self.failure_counts[idx] +| 1;\n        self.failure_counts[idx] = new_count;\n\n        if (new_count >= self.unhealthy_threshold) {\n            self.markUnhealthy(idx);\n            self.failure_counts[idx] = 0;\n        }\n    }\n```\n\n**Step 4: Run tests**\n\nRun: `zig build test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: All tests PASS (existing + new concurrent write test).\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add serval-health/health_state.zig serval-health/tests.zig\ngit commit -m \"fix(health): add mutex to protect counter read-modify-write from data race\n\nPassive health updates (request path) and active probing (background thread)\nboth write failure_counts/success_counts concurrently. Bitmap reads remain\nlock-free.\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Validate upstream.idx at LB init (Finding 2 - High)\n\n`onLog` uses `entry.upstream.idx` as an array index into health state. No init-time check ensures each upstream's idx forms a dense 0..N-1 range. In release builds (asserts stripped), an out-of-range or non-dense idx silently corrupts health state.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `serval-lb/handler.zig`\n\n**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd tests to `serval-lb/handler.zig` that verify init rejects non-dense upstream indices.\n\n```zig\ntest \"LbHandler init rejects non-dense upstream idx\" {\n    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8002, .idx = 5 }, // gap: should be 1\n    };\n\n    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n    try std.testing.expectError(error.InvalidUpstreamIndex, result);\n}\n\ntest \"LbHandler init rejects duplicate upstream idx\" {\n    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8002, .idx = 0 }, // duplicate\n    };\n\n    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n    try std.testing.expectError(error.InvalidUpstreamIndex, result);\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: Compile error (error.InvalidUpstreamIndex doesn't exist yet) or assertion panic.\n\n**Step 3: Add idx validation to LbHandler.init**\n\nAdd a validation block in `handler.zig` `init`, after the existing asserts and before setting `self.*`. This validates that upstream indices form a dense 0..N-1 permutation.\n\nKeep `init` return type as `!void` (inferred error set). This is required because `init` also calls `std.Thread.spawn` which returns spawn-related errors not in any named LbError set. The new validation errors (`error.InvalidUpstreamIndex`, `error.TlsContextRequired`) are returned as part of the inferred set alongside existing spawn errors.\n\nAdd validation in `init` after the existing asserts, before `self.* = .{`:\n\n```zig\n        // Validate upstream indices are a dense 0..N-1 permutation.\n        // Prevents health state corruption from misconfigured idx values.\n        var idx_seen: u64 = 0;\n        for (upstreams) |upstream| {\n            if (upstream.idx >= upstreams.len) return error.InvalidUpstreamIndex;\n            const mask: u64 = @as(u64, 1) << @as(u6, @intCast(upstream.idx));\n            if (idx_seen & mask != 0) return error.InvalidUpstreamIndex; // duplicate\n            idx_seen |= mask;\n        }\n```\n\n**Step 4: Run tests**\n\nRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: All tests PASS.\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add serval-lb/handler.zig\ngit commit -m \"fix(lb): validate upstream.idx is dense 0..N-1 at init\n\nPrevents health state corruption from misconfigured idx values.\nReturns error.InvalidUpstreamIndex instead of relying on debug asserts.\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Validate TLS context at init when upstreams require TLS (Finding 3 - Medium)\n\nIf any upstream has `tls=true` but `client_ctx` is null, probes silently fail (client returns `TlsHandshakeFailed`, adapter catches as `false`). The backend stays permanently unhealthy with no indication of misconfiguration.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `serval-lb/handler.zig`\n\n**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nNote: The existing assert at `handler.zig:85` checks `!enable_probing or dns_resolver != null` and would panic before the TLS check if `dns_resolver` is null with probing enabled. The test must provide a valid `dns_resolver` to reach the TLS validation path.\n\n```zig\ntest \"LbHandler init rejects null client_ctx when upstream has tls=true\" {\n    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0, .tls = true },\n    };\n\n    // Provide dns_resolver so the existing probing assert at handler.zig:85 passes.\n    // The TLS validation fires after that assert.\n    var dns_resolver: DnsResolver = undefined;\n    DnsResolver.init(&dns_resolver, .{});\n\n    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n    const result = handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = true }, null, &dns_resolver);\n    try std.testing.expectError(error.TlsContextRequired, result);\n}\n\ntest \"LbHandler init accepts null client_ctx when no upstream has tls\" {\n    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0, .tls = false },\n    };\n\n    var handler: LbHandler = undefined;\n    // probing disabled so dns_resolver=null is fine, and no TLS upstreams so client_ctx=null is fine\n    try handler.init(&upstreams, .{ .enable_probing = false }, null, null);\n    defer handler.deinit();\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: FAIL (error.TlsContextRequired doesn't exist yet).\n\n**Step 3: Add TLS context validation**\n\nIn `handler.zig` `init`, add after the idx validation:\n\n```zig\n        // Validate TLS context when probing is enabled and any upstream requires TLS.\n        // Without client_ctx, TLS probes silently fail and backends stay permanently unhealthy.\n        // Only relevant when probing is active — without probing, no TLS handshakes are attempted\n        // by the LbHandler (request-path TLS uses its own client_ctx from the Client).\n        if (lb_config.enable_probing and client_ctx == null) {\n            for (upstreams) |upstream| {\n                if (upstream.tls) return error.TlsContextRequired;\n            }\n        }\n```\n\n**Step 4: Run tests**\n\nRun: `zig build test-lb 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: All tests PASS.\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add serval-lb/handler.zig\ngit commit -m \"fix(lb): reject null client_ctx when upstreams require TLS\n\nWithout TLS context, probes silently fail and backends stay permanently\nunhealthy. Now returns error.TlsContextRequired at init.\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Reduce prober shutdown latency (Finding 4 - Medium)\n\n`runLoopWithIo` sleeps for the full probe interval (default 5s) then checks `probe_running`. `deinit()` sets the flag then blocks on `join()`. Worst-case shutdown blocks for the full interval.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `serval-prober/scheduler.zig`\n\n**Step 1: Write the test**\n\nThe existing `probeUnhealthyOnce` test covers probe logic. Add a test verifying the shutdown flag is checked between sleep increments. Since we can't easily test timing, we test that the loop exits promptly when `probe_running` is false from the start.\n\n```zig\ntest \"runLoopWithIo exits immediately when probe_running is false\" {\n    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n    };\n\n    var health = HealthState.init(1, 1, 1);\n    var running = std.atomic.Value(bool).init(false); // already stopped\n\n    var adapter_marker: u8 = 0;\n    const NoopAdapter = struct {\n        fn probe(context: *anyopaque, upstream: Upstream, io_arg: Io) bool {\n            _ = context;\n            _ = upstream;\n            _ = io_arg;\n            return false;\n        }\n    };\n\n    const ctx = SchedulerContext{\n        .upstreams = &upstreams,\n        .health = &health,\n        .probe_running = &running,\n        .probe_interval_ms = 60_000, // 60 seconds - would hang if not interruptible\n        .adapter = .{\n            .context = &adapter_marker,\n            .probeFn = NoopAdapter.probe,\n        },\n    };\n\n    // This should return near-instantly, not block for 60 seconds\n    runLoopWithIo(ctx, undefined);\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run test**\n\nRun: `zig build test 2>&1 | grep -A2 \"runLoopWithIo exits\"`\nExpected: PASS (current code already checks flag before sleep, so this passes). The real improvement is the sleep granularity change.\n\n**Step 3: Replace single long sleep with interruptible polling loop**\n\nIn `scheduler.zig`, replace the single `Io.sleep` call with a loop of shorter sleeps (100ms increments) that checks `probe_running` between each:\n\nReplace the `runLoopWithIo` function:\n\n```zig\n/// Maximum sleep granularity for interruptible shutdown (100ms).\nconst SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS: u32 = 100;\n\npub fn runLoopWithIo(ctx: SchedulerContext, io: Io) void {\n    assert(ctx.probe_interval_ms > 0);\n\n    while (ctx.probe_running.load(.acquire)) {\n        probeUnhealthyOnce(ctx, io);\n        // Sleep in small increments so shutdown is responsive.\n        interruptibleSleep(ctx.probe_running, ctx.probe_interval_ms, io);\n    }\n}\n\n/// Sleep for `total_ms` in increments of SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS, checking the\n/// stop flag between each increment. Returns early if flag becomes false.\nfn interruptibleSleep(\n    probe_running: *std.atomic.Value(bool),\n    total_ms: u32,\n    io: Io,\n) void {\n    var remaining_ms: u32 = total_ms;\n    while (remaining_ms > 0 and probe_running.load(.acquire)) {\n        const sleep_ms = @min(remaining_ms, SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS);\n        const duration = std.Io.Duration.fromMilliseconds(@intCast(sleep_ms));\n        std.Io.sleep(std.Options.debug_io, duration, .awake) catch |err| {\n            log.debug(\"interruptible sleep failed: {s}\", .{@errorName(err)});\n        };\n        remaining_ms -= sleep_ms;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Step 4: Run tests**\n\nRun: `zig build test 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: All PASS. Note: there is no dedicated `test-prober` build step; `zig build test` runs all library tests including the prober scheduler tests.\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add serval-prober/scheduler.zig\ngit commit -m \"fix(prober): reduce shutdown latency with interruptible sleep\n\nReplaces single long sleep with 100ms polling loop that checks\nprobe_running between increments. Worst-case shutdown delay is\nnow ~100ms instead of the full probe interval.\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 5: Update serval-lb README (Finding 5 - Low)\n\nThe usage example calls `handler.init` with old 2-arg signature; current API requires `client_ctx` and `dns_resolver`. The struct snippet shows fields (`health`, `next_idx`) that now live in `RoundRobinStrategy`.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `serval-lb/README.md`\n\n**Step 1: Update usage example**\n\nChange the init call at line 44 to match current signature:\n\n```zig\nvar handler: serval_lb.LbHandler = undefined;\ntry handler.init(&upstreams, .{\n    .unhealthy_threshold = 3,\n    .healthy_threshold = 2,\n    .probe_interval_ms = 5000,\n    .probe_timeout_ms = 2000,\n    .health_path = \"/health\",\n}, client_ctx, &dns_resolver);\ndefer handler.deinit();\n```\n\n**Step 2: Update struct snippet**\n\nReplace the LbHandler struct snippet (line 57) to match actual fields:\n\n```zig\npub const LbHandler = struct {\n    upstreams: []const Upstream,\n    strategy: RoundRobinStrategy,\n    probe_running: std.atomic.Value(bool),\n    probe_thread: ?std.Thread,\n    lb_config: LbConfig,\n\n    pub fn init(self: *Self, upstreams: []const Upstream, lb_config: LbConfig, client_ctx: ?*ssl.SSL_CTX, dns_resolver: ?*DnsResolver) !void\n    pub fn deinit(self: *Self) void\n    pub fn selectUpstream(self: *Self, ctx: *Context, request: *const Request) Upstream\n    pub fn onLog(self: *Self, ctx: *Context, entry: LogEntry) void\n    pub fn countHealthy(self: *const Self) u32\n    pub fn isHealthy(self: *const Self, idx: UpstreamIndex) bool\n};\n```\n\n**Step 3: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add serval-lb/README.md\ngit commit -m \"docs(lb): update README to match current init signature and struct fields\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 6: Run full test suite\n\n**Step 1: Run all unit tests**\n\nRun: `zig build test 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: All PASS.\n\n**Step 2: Run LB and health tests specifically**\n\nRun: `zig build test-lb test-health 2>&1 | tail -20`\nExpected: All PASS.\n","numLines":512,"startLine":1,"totalLines":512}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b05188dc-f4ef-40ac-adea-e3d15521c3a3","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/home/nick/repos/serval","sessionId":"646a4f49-bebb-4328-acf0-8f573ea592f5","version":"2.1.86","gitBranch":"main","slug":"graceful-swimming-stream"}
