### Task 4: Reduce prober shutdown latency (Finding 4 - Medium)\n348\t\n349\t`runLoopWithIo` sleeps for the full probe interval (default 5s) then checks `probe_running`. `deinit()` sets the flag then blocks on `join()`. Worst-case shutdown blocks for the full interval.\n350\t\n351\t**Files:**\n352\t- Modify: `serval-prober/scheduler.zig`\n353\t\n354\t**Step 1: Write tests**\n355\t\n356\tTwo tests: one for immediate exit (flag false at entry), one for mid-sleep cancellation (flag flips while sleeping). The mid-sleep test spawns `runLoopWithIo` on a background thread with a long interval, flips the flag after a short delay, and asserts the thread joins well before the full interval elapses.\n357\t\n358\t```zig\n359\ttest \"runLoopWithIo exits immediately when probe_running is false\" {\n360\t    const upstreams = [_]Upstream{\n361\t        .{ .host = \"127.0.0.1\", .port = 8001, .idx = 0 },\n362\t    };\n363\t\n364\t    var health = HealthState.init(1, 1, 1);\n365\t    var running = std.atomic.Value(bool).init(false); // already stopped\n366\t\n367\t    var adapter_marker: u8 = 0;\n368\t    const NoopAdapter = struct {\n369\t        fn probe(context: *anyopaque, upstream: Upstream, io_arg: Io) bool {\n370\t            _ = context;\n371\t            _ = upstream;\n372\t            _ = io_arg;\n373\t            return false;\n374\t        }\n375\t    };\n376\t\n377\t    const ctx = SchedulerContext{\n378\t        .upstreams = &upstreams,\n379\t        .health = &health,\n380\t        .probe_running = &running,\n381\t        .probe_interval_ms = 60_000, // 60 seconds - would hang if not interruptible\n382\t        .adapter = .{\n383\t            .context = &adapter_marker,\n384\t            .probeFn = NoopAdapter.probe,\n385\t        },\n386\t    };\n387\t\n388\t    // This should return near-instantly, not block for 60 seconds\n389\t    runLoopWithIo(ctx, undefined);\n390\t}\n391\t\n392\ttest \"interruptibleSleep exits early when flag flips mid-sleep\" {\n393\t    var running = std.atomic.Value(bool).init(true);\n394\t\n395\t    // Spawn interruptibleSleep on a background thread with a 10-second total sleep.\n396\t    const worker = struct {\n397\t        fn run(probe_running: *std.atomic.Value(bool)) void {\n398\t            // Use undefined Io — interruptibleSleep only needs it for Io.sleep,\n399\t            // and the real Io.Threaded is not needed for this timing test.\n400\t            // In production the caller provides a real Io.\n401\t            var io_runtime = std.Io.Threaded.init(std.heap.page_allocator, .{});\n402\t            defer io_runtime.deinit();\n403\t            interruptibleSleep(probe_running, 10_000, io_runtime.io());\n404\t        }\n405\t    }.run;\n406\t\n407\t    const thread = std.Thread.spawn(.{}, worker, .{&running}) catch unreachable;\n408\t\n409\t    // Wait 300ms then flip the flag — well past one SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS (100ms) cycle\n410\t    // but well under the 10-second total sleep.\n411\t    const delay = std.Io.Duration.fromMilliseconds(300);\n412\t    std.Io.sleep(std.Options.debug_io, delay, .awake) catch {};\n413\t\n414\t    running.store(false, .release);\n415\t\n416\t    // Thread should join promptly (within ~100ms of flag flip).\n417\t    // If interruptibleSleep were a single 10s sleep, this would hang for ~9.7s.\n418\t    thread.join();\n419\t\n420\t    // If we got here, the interruptible sleep exited early. Success.\n421\t}\n422\t```\n423\t\n424\t**Step 2: Run tests**\n425\t\n426\tRun: `zig build test`\n427\tExpected: Both PASS. Verify exit code 0. The mid-sleep test confirms the thread joins in ~400ms total, not 10 seconds.\n428\t\n429\t**Step 3: Replace single long sleep with interruptible polling loop**\n430\t\n431\tIn `scheduler.zig`, replace the single `Io.sleep` call with a loop of shorter sleeps (100ms increments) that checks `probe_running` between each:\n432\t\n433\tReplace the `runLoopWithIo` function:\n434\t\n435\t```zig\n436\t/// Maximum sleep granularity for interruptible shutdown (100ms).\n437\tconst SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS: u32 = 100;\n438\t\n439\tpub fn runLoopWithIo(ctx: SchedulerContext, io: Io) void {\n440\t    assert(ctx.probe_interval_ms > 0);\n441\t\n442\t    while (ctx.probe_running.load(.acquire)) {\n443\t        probeUnhealthyOnce(ctx, io);\n444\t        // Sleep in small increments so shutdown is responsive.\n445\t        interruptibleSleep(ctx.probe_running, ctx.probe_interval_ms, io);\n446\t    }\n447\t}\n448\t\n449\t/// Sleep for `total_ms` in increments of SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS, checking the\n450\t/// stop flag between each increment. Returns early if flag becomes false.\n451\t/// Visible to tests for direct validation of mid-sleep cancellation.\n452\tpub fn interruptibleSleep(\n453\t    probe_running: *std.atomic.Value(bool),\n454\t    total_ms: u32,\n455\t    io: Io,\n456\t) void {\n457\t    var remaining_ms: u32 = total_ms;\n458\t    while (remaining_ms > 0 and probe_running.load(.acquire)) {\n459\t        const sleep_ms = @min(remaining_ms, SHUTDOWN_POLL_MS);\n460\t        const duration = std.Io.Duration.fromMilliseconds(@intCast(sleep_ms));\n461\t        std.Io.sleep(std.Options.debug_io, duration, .awake) catch |err| {\n462\t            log.debug(\"interruptible sleep failed: {s}\", .{@errorName(err)});\n463\t        };\n464\t        remaining_ms -= sleep_ms;\n465\t    }\n466\t}\n467\t```\n468\t\n469\t**Step 4: Run tests**\n470\t\n471\tRun: `zig build test`\n472\tExpected: All PASS. Verify exit code 0. Note: there is no dedicated `test-prober` build step; `zig build test` runs all library tests including the prober scheduler tests.\n473\t\n474\t**Step 5: Commit**\n475\t\n476\t```bash\n477\tgit add serval-prober/scheduler.zig\n478\tgit commit -m \"fix(prober): reduce shutdown latency with interruptible sleep\n479\t\n480\tReplaces single long sleep with 100ms polling loop that checks\n481\tprobe_running between increments. Worst-case shutdown delay is\n482\tnow ~100ms instead of the full probe interval.\"\n483\t```\n484\